"Shongwe M.E., van Oldenborgh G.J., van den Hurk B., van Aalst M.","Projected changes in mean and extreme precipitation in Africa under global warming. Part II: East Africa",2011,"Journal of Climate","24","14",,"3718","3733",,,10.1175/2010JCLI2883.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79960521848&partnerID=40&md5=06ba963579c2f5eb9ddf699fc20572c5","Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute, De Bilt, Netherlands; Red Cross/Red Crescent Climate Centre, The Hague, Netherlands; South African Weather Service, Pretoria, South Africa","Shongwe, M.E., Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute, De Bilt, Netherlands, South African Weather Service, Pretoria, South Africa; van Oldenborgh, G.J., Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute, De Bilt, Netherlands; van den Hurk, B., Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute, De Bilt, Netherlands; van Aalst, M., Red Cross/Red Crescent Climate Centre, The Hague, Netherlands","Probable changes in mean and extreme precipitation in East Africa are estimated from general circulation models (GCMs) prepared for the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Fourth Assessment Report (AR4). Bayesian statistics are used to derive the relative weights assigned to each member in the multimodel ensemble. There is substantial evidence in support of a positive shift of the whole rainfall distribution in East Africa during the wet seasons. The models give indications for an increase in mean precipitation rates and intensity of high rainfall events but for less severe droughts. Upward precipitation trends are projected from early this (twenty first) century. As in the observations, a statistically significant link between sea surface temperature gradients in the tropical Indian Ocean and short rains (October-December) in East Africa is simulated in the GCMs. Furthermore, most models project a differential warming of the Indian Ocean during boreal autumn. This is favorable for an increase in the probability of positive Indian Ocean zonal mode events, which have been associated with anomalously strong short rains in East Africa. On top of the general increase in rainfall in the tropics due to thermodynamic effects, a change in the structure of the Eastern Hemisphere Walker circulation is consistent with an increase in East Africa precipitation relative to other regions within the same latitudinal belt. A notable feature of this change is a weakening of the climatological subsidence over eastern Kenya. East Africa is shown to be a region in which a coherent projection of future precipitation change can be made, supported by physical arguments. Although the rate of change is still uncertain, almost all results point to a wetter climate with more intense wet seasons and less severe droughts. © 2011 American Meteorological Society.","Africa; Extreme events; Indian Ocean; Precipitation; Sea surface temperature; Statistical techniques; Subsidence","Africa; Extreme events; Indian Ocean; Sea surface temperatures; Statistical techniques; Atmospheric temperature; Climate models; Computer simulation; Drought; Global warming; Oceanography; Subsidence; Surface properties; Tropics; Rain; Bayesian analysis; drought; extreme event; general circulation model; global warming; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; precipitation (climatology); rainfall; sea surface temperature; temperature gradient; thermodynamics; Walker circulation; East Africa; Eastern Hemisphere; Indian Ocean; Indian Ocean (Tropical)",,,,,,"Anyah, R.O., Semazzi, F.H.M., Variability of East African rainfall based on multiyear RegCM3 simulations (2007) Int. J. Climatol., 27, pp. 357-371; Behera, S.K., Luo, J.-J., Masson, S., Delecluse, P., Gualdi, S., Navarra, A., Yagamata, T., Paramount impact of the Indian Ocean dipole on the East African short rains:ACGCM study (2005) J. Climate, 18, pp. 4514-4530; Beniston, M., Future extreme events in European climate: An exploration of regional climate model projections (2007) Climate Change, 81, pp. 71-95. , doi:10.1007/s10584-006-9226-z; Black, E., Slingo, J., Sperber, K.R., An observational study of the relationship between excessively strong short rains in coastal East Africa and Indian Ocean SST (2003) Mon. Wea. Rev., 131, pp. 74-94; Chen, T.-C., Maintenance of the midtropospheric north African summer circulation: Saharan high and African easterly jet (2005) J. Climate, 18, pp. 2943-2962; Clark, C.O., Webster, P.J., Cole, J.E., Interdecadal variability of the relationship between the Indian Ocean zonal mode and East African coastal rainfall anomalies (2003) J. Climate, 16, pp. 548-554; Coles, S., (2001) An Introduction to Statistical Modeling of Extreme Values, p. 208. , Springer; Gillett, N.P., Weaver, A.J., Zwiers, .F., Flannigan, M.D., Detecting the effect of human-induced climate change on Canadian forest fires (2004) Geophys. Res. Lett., 31, pp. L18211. , doi:10.1029/2004GL020876; Giorgi, F., Francisco, R., Uncertainties in regional climate change predictions: A regional analysis of ensemble simulations with the HADCM2 GCM (2000) Climate Dyn., 16, pp. 169-182; Giorgi, F., Mearns, L.O., Calculation of average, uncertainty range, and reliability of regional climate changes from AOGCM simulations via the ""Reliability Ensemble Average"" (REA) method (2002) J. Climate, 15, pp. 1141-1158; Giorgi, F., Mearns, L.O., Probability of regional climate change based on Reliability Ensemble Average (REA) method (2003) Geophys. Res. Lett., 30, p. 1629. , doi:10.1029/2003GL017130; Goddard, L., Graham, N.E., The importance of the Indian Ocean for simulating rainfall anomalies over eastern and southern Africa (1999) J. Geophys. Res., 104, pp. 19099-19116; Hastenrath, S., Polzin, D., Mechanisms of climate anomalies in the equatorial Indian Ocean (2005) J. Geophys. Res., 110, pp. D08113. , doi:10.1029/2004JD004981; Hastenrath, S., Nicklis, A., Greischar, L., Atmospheric-hydrospheric mechanisms of climate anomalies in the western equatorial Indian Ocean (1993) J. Geophys. Res